0. Introduction¶

This Python notebook demonstrates a step-by-step process for detecting spam SMS messages by building and comparing various machine learning classification models. Our goal is to explore the performance of different algorithms and identify the best model for accurately classifying SMS as spam or not.

The classification models we evaluate include:

  • Logistic Regression (LR)
  • Decision Tree Classifier (DT)
  • Random Forest Classifier (RF)
  • Support Vector Classifier (SVC)
  • K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier (K-NN)
  • Multinomial Naive Bayes
  • AdaBoost Classifier
  • Bagging Classifier (Bgc)
  • Gradient Boosting Decision Trees (GBDT)
  • XGBoost Classifier
  • Extra Trees Classifier (ETC)

By comparing these models, we aim to determine which algorithm offers the best performance for detecting spam in SMS messages, ensuring both accuracy and efficiency.

5. Data Preprocessing¶

In [455]:
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))

# Creating an instance of the Porter Stemmer
stemmer = PorterStemmer()

def preprocess_text(text):
    # Lower case
    text = text.lower()

    # Tokenize the text
    tokens = word_tokenize(text)
    
    # Remove special characters, stopwords and punctuation
    tokens = [word for word in tokens if word.isalnum() and word not in stop_words and word not in string.punctuation]
    
    # Perform stemming
    tokens = [stemmer.stem(word) for word in tokens]
    
    # Join tokens back into a string
    text = ' '.join(tokens)

    return text

df['transformed_message'] = df['message'].apply(preprocess_text)

# Function to plot bar charts for word frequency
def plot_word_frequency(df, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.barplot(data = df, x = df[0], y = df[1], palette = 'bright')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel('Words')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

In [463]:
# Train the models, make predictions, and return evaluation metrics
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_tfidf, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
def train_models(clfs, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    clfs.fit(X_train,y_train)
    y_pred = clfs.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    report = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)
    confus_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

    return accuracy , precision, report, confus_matrix
In [464]:
# Print the performance of each model
for name , clfs in clfs.items():
    accuracy, precision, report, confus_matrix = train_models(clfs, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test)
    print()
    print("Model: ", name)
    print("Accuracy: ", accuracy)
    print("Precision: ", precision)
    print("Classfication Report: \n", report)
    print("confusion_matrix: \n", confus_matrix)

Comments on the model performances:¶

  1. Support Vector Classifier (SVC):

    • Accuracy: 98.36%, Precision: 97.76%
    • Comment: The SVC performs exceptionally well with both high accuracy and precision. The confusion matrix shows only a few false negatives (14), indicating that most spam messages are detected accurately, though some spam messages are still missed.
    • Strength: Excellent overall performance with good balance across precision, recall, and f1-score.

  2. K-Nearest Neighbors (K-NN):

    • Accuracy: 89.94%, Precision: 100%
    • Comment: While the precision is perfect, the recall for spam messages (class 1) is poor at 28%, meaning many spam messages are not being detected. The confusion matrix shows that 104 spam messages were incorrectly classified as non-spam.
    • Weakness: Very low recall for spam detection, indicating this model is overly conservative in labeling spam.

  3. Multinomial Naive Bayes:

    • Accuracy: 95.55%, Precision: 100%
    • Comment: This model achieves perfect precision but struggles with recall for spam (68%). While it detects non-spam perfectly, it misses some spam messages. This may be typical for Naive Bayes with imbalanced classes.
    • Strength: High precision, meaning it rarely misclassifies non-spam as spam.

  4. Decision Tree Classifier:

    • Accuracy: 95.55%, Precision: 95.41%
    • Comment: The Decision Tree shows strong performance, but recall for spam is only 72%. It's still missing quite a few spam messages (41), though its accuracy and overall performance are solid.
    • Strength: Balanced performance but could improve on recall for spam.

  5. Logistic Regression:

    • Accuracy: 95.74%, Precision: 92.44%
    • Comment: Logistic Regression offers a good balance, though recall for spam is 76%, missing some spam messages. The model achieves strong overall accuracy and reasonable f1-scores.
    • Strength: Solid all-around performance but slightly lower precision and recall compared to other models.

  6. Random Forest Classifier:

    • Accuracy: 97.68%, Precision: 99.19%
    • Comment: Random Forest performs exceptionally well with very high accuracy and precision. It has strong recall (84%) for spam but still misclassifies 23 spam messages as non-spam.
    • Strength: Excellent overall accuracy and performance across all metrics.

  7. AdaBoost Classifier:

    • Accuracy: 98.16%, Precision: 96.32%
    • Comment: AdaBoost delivers strong results with good precision and recall for spam (90%). It misses only 14 spam messages, making it a reliable option.
    • Strength: Very balanced with high precision and recall, making it a strong performer.

  8. Bagging Classifier:

    • Accuracy: 97.78%, Precision: 96.21%
    • Comment: The Bagging Classifier performs similarly to AdaBoost with high precision and recall. It misses 18 spam messages, but overall the model is highly reliable.
    • Strength: Consistent and reliable performance, making it a good choice.

  9. Extra Trees Classifier:

    • Accuracy: 98.07%, Precision: 100%
    • Comment: Extra Trees shows perfect precision and a strong recall (86%) for spam. It performs very well across the board, with only 20 spam messages misclassified.
    • Strength: High precision with a good balance of recall and accuracy.

  10. Gradient Boosting Decision Trees (GBDT):

    • Accuracy: 96.52%, Precision: 98.23%
    • Comment: GBDT shows strong performance with high precision and overall accuracy. The recall for spam (77%) is slightly lower, indicating it misses some spam messages (34).
    • Strength: Reliable and consistent performance, though it could improve spam recall.

  11. XGBoost Classifier:

    • Accuracy: 97.78%, Precision: 96.21%
    • Comment: XGBoost delivers strong results with high accuracy, precision, and recall for spam (88%). Only 18 spam messages are missed, making it one of the top performers.
    • Strength: Excellent balance of precision, recall, and accuracy.

General Observations:¶

  • Top Performers: Support Vector Classifier (SVC), AdaBoost, XGBoost, Random Forest, and Extra Trees Classifier deliver the best balance between precision, recall, and accuracy.
  • K-NN Issue: The K-NN classifier has poor recall for spam messages, making it unsuitable for detecting spam in this dataset despite its perfect precision.
  • Model Choices: Depending on the application, if minimizing false positives (misclassifying non-spam as spam) is critical, models like Multinomial Naive Bayes and Extra Trees Classifier would be ideal due to their perfect precision. If high recall (detecting as much spam as possible) is the goal, models like Support Vector Classifier, Random Forest, or AdaBoost would be preferred.

In conclusion, we think Support Vector Classifier and AdaBoost stand out as the most balanced models for this spam detection task, combining high accuracy, precision, and recall.
